M|felix|> Runs before every financial model, recommendation, P&L, or runway analysis delivered to Marcus or Stark.
M|felix|> Stark sees only Pass 3. Never the process.
M|felix|**Triggers on:** financial models, P&L reports, runway projections, ROI analyses, budget recommendations, any number delivered as a recommendation or forecast.
M|felix|**Does NOT trigger on:** raw data pulls or simple arithmetic checks with no interpretation.
M|felix|Produce the full financial model, report, or recommendation.
M|felix|- Is runway below 6 months? → If yes, this is the first sentence of the output, not buried at the end.
M|felix|- Are all assumptions named explicitly BEFORE any numbers appear — never after?
M|felix|- Is there a downside scenario — a bear case that the plan must survive? If not, it's not a recommendation, it's a wish.
M|felix|- Am I conflating Hourbour MRR (recurring, sticky) with Novizio revenue (transactional, acquisition-dependent) in any summary line?
M|felix|- Does every recommended action have a named DRI — a number without an owner is not a plan?
M|felix|- Would this model survive if the most optimistic assumption is wrong? What breaks first?
M|felix|- Am I leading with the good news to make the report more palatable? Reverse it: worst metric first.
M|felix|Correct everything found in Pass 2. Bear case is not optional. DRI is not optional. Worst number leads. Deliver only Pass 3.
M|felix|> Universal mistakes only — vtr-specific mistakes live in mem-[vtr].md.
M|felix|> Format: [date] — wrong assumption — impact — rule.
M|felix|- [baseline] — Never report a financial recommendation without a named owner for the action. A number without a DRI is a wish, not a plan.
M|felix|- [baseline] — Never consolidate Hourbour MRR and Novizio revenue into a single "total revenue" line without labeling composition. They have different quality and predictability.
M|felix|- [baseline] — Never present a single-scenario financial model as a recommendation. Base case alone is an optimism trap. Always show downside.